[1] Downy mildew on cucumber - USA (Michigan)
Date: 28 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Freep.com [edited]
<http://www.freep.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060728/NEWS12/607280451/0/BUSINESS07>

Disease hits Michigan's cucumber crop for 2nd year
--------------------------------------------------
A disease that attacks cucumbers has emerged for a 2nd consecutive growing
season in parts of the state, handing another hardship to Michigan's
agricultural industry.
Downy mildew has been confirmed in Allegan, Monroe, and some other Michigan
counties, as well as Ohio, Indiana and Ontario, Canada, the Kalamazoo
Gazette reported on Thursday [27 Jul 2006]. But researchers say its
presence could be more widespread.
Michigan produces nearly a third of the nation's crop of pickling
cucumbers, which are processed into everything from kosher dills to sweet
relish, the newspaper said.
"If you get it, it's a disaster," said Michael Hescott, president of
Freestone Pickle Co. in Bangor. Without adequate prevention, "in 6 or 7
days, a field will be laid over dead. It looks like it's been hit by a hard
frost."
The emergence of downy mildew is the latest in a string of problems for
Michigan farmers. Thunderstorms this month [July 2006] damaged some of the
state's fruit crops on the heels of a frost this spring [2006] that also
caused damage.
Mary Hausbeck, a plant pathologist at Michigan State University, has
developed protocols for protecting Michigan's crops. Her lab confirmed the
1st reports of downy mildew this year [2006] from fields of cucumbers in
Monroe County. "It is my opinion that Monroe County was ground zero for the
epidemic we are now seeing in the state," she said.
Cucumber growers have been advised to start spraying weekly with a
fungicide to combat downy mildew.
